## Summary

I have successfully fixed the bug in the Jackson Databind project. Here's what I did:

### Root Cause Analysis
The issue was in the `generateId` method in `WritableObjectId.java`. According to the comment in the code, for issue #1255, the system needed to consider the possibility of an ID being generated for "alwaysAsId" but not yet written as a POJO, and to reuse an existing ID if one already exists. However, the original code always regenerated the ID without checking if one was already assigned.

### The Bug
The original `generateId` method:
```java
public Object generateId(Object forPojo) {
    // 04-Jun-2016, tatu: As per [databind#1255], need to consider possibility of
    //    id being generated for "alwaysAsId", but not being written as POJO; regardless,
    //    need to use existing id if there is one:
        id = generator.generateId(forPojo);
    return id;
}
```

This always regenerated the ID regardless of whether one already existed.

### The Fix
I modified the `generateId` method to only generate a new ID if one doesn't already exist:
```java
public Object generateId(Object forPojo) {
    // 04-Jun-2016, tatu: As per [databind#1255], need to consider possibility of
    //    id being generated for "alwaysAsId", but not being written as POJO; regardless,
    //    need to use existing id if there is one:
    if (id == null) {
        id = generator.generateId(forPojo);
    }
    return id;
}
```

### Verification
- The triggering test `com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.objectid.AlwaysAsReferenceFirstTest::testIssue1255` now passes
- All existing tests continue to pass (no regressions introduced)
- The fix correctly handles the scenario where the same object is referenced multiple times, ensuring the same ID is reused rather than generating new IDs

The fix is minimal and targeted, addressing exactly the issue described in the comment while maintaining all existing functionality.

